 must know there's difference male judge female judge. judge job." side bench, women also working syariah lawyers. number women registered syariah lawyers association, voluntary membership group, increased 200 last five years, make 40 percent group's members. sa'adiah binti din working lawyer secular courts first volunteered syariah legal aid work 18 years ago. says realised many muslim women appearing syariah courts unrepresented, began taking divorce cases. "that turning point," says sa'adiah. "now, i'm syariah court almost every day." says female clients often find less difficult appear female judge court officials. "i believe find easier talk woman," says. malaysian universities, islamic law courses increasingly dominated young women. nur farhana, 22, one growing number young malaysian women studying islamic law university [liz gooch/al jazeera] judge mohd na'im, sits syariah court appeal, says women top performing students classes teaches local institutions. nur farhana, 22, one four students completing internship selangor syariah court june. one women. studying islamic civil law international islamic university malaysia, already decided pursue career islamic law says civil law "man-made law". "most (islamic) laws said quran sunnah, … prefer that," says. farhana may female role models, judge nenney graduated 1998, prospect judge seemed far-fetched. woman ever appointed syariah bench malaysia, simply finding job field tough. "even syariah court officer quite difficult women preferred men," says. "i needed study two years more." returning university complete masters degree, started working lawyer legal aid office moving attorney-general's department. now, says, syariah justice system offers young women good career path. "to me, quite difficult reach position. needed compete male officers," says. "but it's gender now, it's qualification." source: al jazeera author liz gooch liz gooch journalist covering southeast asia. @ liz_gooch law malaysia religion asia
