antioquia, colombia - antioquia heartland colombian gold trade since colonial times, spanish conquerors came search mythical el dorado. northeast province lies segovia, tiny township 400 years produced gold, chiselled walls thousands underground tunnels. afro-descendant indigenous colombians worked artisanal miners decades, using techniques ancestors, spanish enslaved mine land. since early 2000s, price precious metal risen, region experienced violent gold rush leftist guerrillas, neo-paramilitary outfits drug trafficking groups established presence control mining operations. illegally mined gold fuelling violence gold overtaken cocaine main source revenue armed groups. illegal mining colombia brings approximately $7bn year (link spanish) armed groups criminal bands. segovia centre violence. almost 20 percent colombia's gold produced nearly 50 mines operating there, according segovia's mayor's office. local villagers - many artisanal miners - shaken extortions, threats, territorial disputes grudge fights. miners, including rural colombians across country come search work, working mountains riverbanks, forced pay "tax" armed group controls area. informal miners also killed forcibly displaced armed groups. "you pay them. not, kill you," says carlos mario alvarez, 60-year-old mining leader. handful mines owned gran colombia gold, canada-based multinational. one mines includes cogote, successful informal mining cooperative, whose licence colombian government sold canadian multinational. since 2015, president juan manuel santos' administration prioritised cracking unlicensed mining order cut lucrative source income armed groups curb mercury poisoning rivers - traditional miners use chemical separate gold earth metals - environmental damage, conjunction legalisation programme region's traditional miners. many miners feel caught armed groups government's clampdown informal mining. alvarez, "being miner job part colombia, identity." child, he'd bring lunch father mines finishing school. alvarez dropped school start working "catanguero" (a carrier) mines 14 years old. "i'm currently owner mine," says proudly. "but government wants take ... us." alvarez says government's reform unlicensed mining facade. "the government forcing us favour multinational companies," says. "he [santos] wants open way multinational investors buy land."
