slums kenya often private toilets, boosting spread disease risk rape [laila ali/al jazeera] nairobi, kenya - ever attended music festival, chances familiar dreaded panic looking nearest bathroom nature calls. imagine panic, time inside home. however, instead walking corridor bathroom, walk blocks, perhaps dark, nearest toilet - hole ground, reeking stale urine sometimes full waste, shared dozen families. reality many slum dwellers kenya. unsurprisingly, many residents don't bother walk. privacy expediency, opt relieve using plastic bags throw far away possible homes: phenomenon known "flying toilets". landlords reluctant build toilets keep fast-expanding informal settlements, space takes build toilet could build room earn money, said stella kitonga, deputy project manager peepoople , ngo operates nairobi slums. concerned community hygiene potential "flying toilets" spread diseases, peepoople come novel approach tackle problem silanga, village kibera, kenya's biggest slum: self-sanitising, biodegradable bag known "peepoo" people use homes. incredibly, peepoos meet world health organisation's requirement hygiene disease prevention, contain five grams urea, breaks waste ammonia carbonate. bags inner outer layer. inner layer wide tube keep hands clean holding closing. outer layer pulls inner layer ties knot prevent flies small animals coming contact it. odour contained 24 hours. women living slums, added element security using peepoo safety homes. "a number rape cases reported women go outside home look sanitation facilities. come understand since peepoo introduced, reduction rape crime silanga village," says mika mitoko, project manager peepoople. job opportunity bags, subsidised donors, sold 3 kenyan shillings ($0.03) each. bags' small size means also carried used elsewhere. users opt keep waste use garden fertiliser, bags dropped collection point reimbursement 1 shilling ($0.01) per bag. "i didn't regular job peepoos introduced, saw opportunity people want drop bags ." - mama lucy, entrepreneur pageloadedsuccessfully reimbursement intended discourage people dumping bags, unintended effect creating jobs. reluctant carry waste drop designated place, collection service exists. mama lucy, young mother three, makes living collecting used peepoo bags network neighbours friends. pockets reimbursement fees. "i didn't regular job peepoos introduced, saw opportunity people want drop bags themselves," said, handing bucket bags drop-off point. "now, two rounds day pick peepoos people's houses. good week earn thousand shillings ($11)." originally pilot project introduced 2010, peepoo official launch stage, ready implemented parts kibera. however, business tackling slum waste limited ngos. private sector also getting involved turning profit. sanergy , company founded mit business school graduates whose name combines words "santiation" "energy", aims build dense network low-cost sanitation centres named fresh life, distribute franchising local entrepreneurs run small businesses. sanergy collects waste toilets converts useful products biogas organic fertiliser, sold number co-operatives. partnered kiva , microfinancing organisation provides small loans entrepreneurs wish purchase fresh life toilet. according sanergy co-founder david auerback, business model simple enough: research showed need willingness pay "three five kenyan shillings ($0.03-0.05) use sanitation facilities - came price". fresh life facility managers boost profit selling additional products toilet paper sanitary pads. auerback added business profitable many entrepreneurs running fresh life toilets doubling purchasing another - proof, says, dealing slum waste "viable business". follow laila ali twitter: @lailainnairobi source: al jazeera author laila ali kenya
