arba khatun, 50 [katie arnold/al jazeera] arba khatun , 50, comes rakhine state, myanmar , fled weeks ago. "my name arba khatun 50 years old. crisis, lived fairly good life: domestic animals, farm, cultivated lots different crops like rice coconuts. somehow, managed. husband died 15 years ago, lived son family. younger, used love working farm, old, son work. remember day was, woken washing face military came farm stole animals. fired gun bullet hit stomach. luckily, go deep, painful bleeding lot son took nearby doctor. returned whole village burned ground. son carried mountain, found family. slept three days, carried bangladesh . could bring anything us son carrying wife carrying two children - difficult journey took us 12 days. heard problems border, crossed easily. happy bangladesh safe here. wound healing walking around lot more, too. could bring food us nothing eat - received support, hungry. son would ask world help us get country back, don't want go again, never safe myanmar, need best bangladesh." *as told katie arnold kutupalong new shelter camp near cox's bazar, bangladesh. *this interview edited clarity. read related article find myanmar's rohingya plight myanmar's rohingya 400,000 rohingya , mainly women children, fled bangladesh recent weeks result indiscriminate violence civilian populations carried myanmar army. un human rights organisations warned mass exodus following killings, rapes, burned villages signs "ethnic cleansing" , pleading international community pressure aung san suu kyi government end violence. "the situation seems textbook example ethnic cleansing," un human rights chief zeid ra'ad al-hussein said monday, september 11. interactive: refugee settlements near cox's bazar bangladesh maps [al jazeera] source: al jazeera author katie arnold @ kate_arno rohingya humanitarian crises profiles rohingya asia
nasima, khatun, 60 [katie arnold/al jazeera] nasima khatun, 60, comes rakhine state, myanmar , fled weeks ago. "my name nasima khatun 60 years old. lived quite life crisis, husband fisherman three daughters - lived well rohingya . although encountered pressure military, face problems regards food shelter. military started firing guns village ran different directions. hiding jungle someone told husband shot. felt helpless afraid. military took village could return bring back body, leave quickly move bangladesh . travelled daughters neighbours village, could carry anything us ate drank whatever found way. one day, passed abandoned shop looted - real food ate 10-day journey; hungry. cried cried whole way neighbours took pity paid boat trip across bangladesh. sad leave myanmar, lost husband there, house, land everything own. we've managed build shelter here, local bangladeshis supported us food donations. opportunity earn money, work us do. type future don't money? everyone wants go back myanmar don't think ever possible, never safe again. go back we'll either tortured killed. believe world watching situation. request empathise - world hears stories sorrow death imagines would feel shoes." *as told katie arnold kutupalong new shelter camp near cox's bazar, bangladesh. *this interview edited clarity. plight myanmar's rohingya 400,000 rohingya , mainly women children, fled bangladesh recent weeks result indiscriminate violence civilian populations carried myanmar army. un human rights organisations warned mass exodus following killings, rapes, burned villages signs "ethnic cleansing" , pleading international community pressure aung san suu kyi government end violence. "the situation seems textbook example ethnic cleansing," un human rights chief zeid ra'ad al-hussein said monday, september 11. interactive: refugee settlements near cox's bazar bangladesh maps [al jazeera] read find myanmar's rohingya source: al jazeera author katie arnold @ kate_arno rohingya profiles rohi