un peacekeepers sent war-ravaged countries earth, ostensibly help transition peace. stand accused committing crimes people supposed protect. according recent investigation associated press, 2004 2016, united nations received almost 2,000 allegations sexual exploitation abuse peacekeepers. un says zero tolerance policy sexual exploitation abuse, survivors, activists, lawyers human rights organisations say crimes allowed continue impunity. conversations un peacekeepers officials, gender experts, academics, researchers activists, well investigation un data, try navigate competing accounts answer question: peacekeepers become predators? history immunity? when, end world war ii , un conceived peacekeepers made immune prosecution host state alleged crimes committed mission. considered necessary stop others sabotaging efforts assist post-conflict environments. instead, would held accountable government judicial system. decades later, however, became apparent peacekeepers abusing privileged position. envisioned immunity would become problematic fiona tate, queen mary university according fiona tate, phd candidate studying law queen mary university london uk , part problem much deeper roots. un first started deploying peacekeepers 1948, didn't consider rights women children militarised environments peacekeepers would operating. "as result exclusion, crimes committed [women] would go largely unrecorded," explains tate. early 1990s, crimes started come international attention. since reports rape democratic republic congo , eriteria, mozambique, somalia , prostitution trafficking bosnia liberia abuse minors sierra leone . 1992, department peacekeeping operations set up. 1994, un appointed graca machel, former first lady mozambique , investigate effects armed conflict children. landmark report, released august 1996, one first raise issue sexual exploitation children peacekeepers call end impunity perpetrators. 2001, discovered aid workers un peacekeepers sexually abused refugees